    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.13-15_0001b" />
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE ARMY AND NAVY CLUB.
                        <lb/>
                    WASHINGTON.</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Feb. 20, 1920.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt, Esq.,</addrLine>
                            <addrLine>Bancroft, Neb.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>My dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I beg to acknowledge your form of the 14th instant with enclosures and am much interested in your <unclear>work</unclear>. By to-day's mail I send you "The Passing of Crazy Horse," which I wrote for 
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.13-15_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">14</fw>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">W.S.I.</hi> Magazine. In same number read Gen. Lee's story on same subject. Some years ago I wrote "Among the Arrapahoes<sic>Arapahoes</sic>" and the "Story of Featherhead" for Harper's magazine, but as the one is a sketch and the other a story, they would probably not serve your purpose.</p>
                
                <p>I knew Forsyth slightly and played <unclear>poker</unclear> with Custer, who was a regular frontiers-man and fond of the game. In fact, the War Department is said to have called him to ac-
                
                <!--page probably missing here-->
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.13-15_0003"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                    Miles with his regiment (<unclear>sit Inkty.</unclear>) mounted upon Indian ponies, was really a better head against the Sioux than Crook, who won his fame against the <unclear>dismounted</unclear> Apaches of Arizona.</p>
                
                <p>The rides of Chief Joseph and of the Cheyennes returning North, are wonderful epics in themselves.</p>
                
                <p>At Wounded Knee <add>^Hawthorne</add> gave the Sioux "bad medicine" in the shape of shells form a platoon of artillery. This they could not answer and they never stood again.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very truly yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>H.R. Lemly</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
